      <hedline>
        <hl1>Movie Violence: Too Much Ado?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gregory J Hanson letter scores 'Hollywood elite' that has perpetrated 'decay' of society (Sept 17 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Richard Rhodes tears apart studies that purport to show a correlation between media violence and violence in the public arena (''Hollow Claims About Fantasy Violence,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 17).</p>
        <p>Then he speculates that many politicians ''use the issue as a smokescreen to avoid having to confront gun control.'' So Hollywood is as pure as the driven snow, while guns are the problem.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Richard Rhodes tears apart studies that purport to show a correlation between media violence and violence in the public arena (''Hollow Claims About Fantasy Violence,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 17).</p>
        <p>Then he speculates that many politicians ''use the issue as a smokescreen to avoid having to confront gun control.'' So Hollywood is as pure as the driven snow, while guns are the problem.</p>
        <p>It seems to me that too many politicians advocate gun control in order to avoid having to confront the human decay of our society and the Hollywood elite that has perpetrated it.  GREGORY J. HANSON  Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Sept. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
